Are there certain spatial configurations
more favorable

4
00:00:16,004 --> 00:00:18,502
to the three pillars
of sustainable development?

5
00:00:19,190 --> 00:00:22,346
The following documents show that 
the city – that's to say

6
00:00:22,475 --> 00:00:26,743
the urban configuration maximizing
density and diversity –

7
00:00:26,841 --> 00:00:31,374
at its best, clearly satisfies
the requirements

8
00:00:31,374 --> 00:00:34,429
of sustainable development’s 
three pillars.

9
00:00:35,446 --> 00:00:39,335
First of all, the compact city is
the best solution for developing

10
00:00:39,496 --> 00:00:43,151
a post-predatory approach to 
natural resources.

11
00:00:43,608 --> 00:00:47,355
At this point it can clearly be seen
how the spatial logics

12
00:00:47,355 --> 00:00:50,452
of farming and industry 
are the problems.

13
00:00:51,026 --> 00:00:53,695
These two sectors,
 are in contradiction

14
00:00:53,823 --> 00:00:58,320
with urban rationales,
as the city is the solution.

15
00:00:58,664 --> 00:01:03,043
As can be seen in Session 5,
however, urban sprawl,

16
00:01:03,235 --> 00:01:06,644
or the ‘Johannesburg’ model,
is not a good answer.

17
00:01:08,217 --> 00:01:11,301
The more an urban area is scattered
and fragmented,

18
00:01:11,536 --> 00:01:16,705
the more negatively it will impact
upon natural environments.

19
00:01:17,959 --> 00:01:21,105
The pillar of economic growth
was analyzed in Session 5.

20
